  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and evolved over several decades:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Initial anti-money laundering (AML) efforts emerged in the 1920s and 1930s\n- Primarily focused on combating organized crime, particularly during Prohibition era in the United States\n\n2. Key Developmental Milestones:\n- 1970: Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) in the United States first established reporting requirements for financial transactions\n- 1986: Money Laundering Control Act in the U.S. criminalized money laundering as a federal crime\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established to develop international AML standards\n\n3. International Expansion:\n- 1990s: Growing international cooperation on AML efforts\n- United Nations conventions addressed money laundering as a global financial crime\n- Increasing regulatory frameworks across multiple jurisdictions\n\n4. Post-9/11 Developments:\n- Patriot Act expanded AML regulations\n- Enhanced focus on preventing terrorist financing\n- Stricter international reporting and compliance requirements\n\n5. Modern Era:\n- Continuous technological adaptations\n- Increased digital currency and cryptocurrency regulations\n- Ongoing global collaboration to prevent financial crimes\n\nThe legal framework continues to evolve with technological and financial innovations.",
